In [2]:
# Function to download specified file extension from given Google cloud location to this VM.

def downloadSpecificFile(bucket, path, fileExtension):
    fileNameList = []
    blobs = bucket.list_blobs(prefix = path, delimiter = '/')
    for blob in blobs:
        if(blob.name != path):
            fullName = blob.name
            res = fullName.find(fileExtension)
            if (res >= 0):
                file_name = blob.name.replace(path, "")
                blob.download_to_filename(file_name) # download the file to the machine
                fileNameList.append(file_name)
    return fileNameList

In [33]:
# Creating Separate dataframes as per Potential Accident level.
Pal_I   = df[df['Potential Accident Level'] == 'I']
Pal_II  = df[df['Potential Accident Level'] == 'II']
Pal_III = df[df['Potential Accident Level'] == 'III']
Pal_IV  = df[df['Potential Accident Level'] == 'IV']
Pal_V   = df[df['Potential Accident Level'] == 'V']
In [34]:
# Using NLPAug package to fillin imbalance data. Here NLPAug is using GLoVe model for augmentation.
aug_w2v = naw.WordEmbsAug(model_type='glove', model_path=gloveFile100d, action="substitute")
In [35]:
# Augment 93 records for Potential Accident Level - I
Pal_I_Sample_Df   = Pal_I.sample(n=93, replace=True)

# Augment 50 records for Potential Accident Level - II
Pal_II_Sample_Df  = Pal_II.sample(n=50, replace=True)

# Augment 36 records for Potential Accident Level - III
Pal_III_Sample_Df = Pal_III.sample(n=36, replace=True)

# Augment 113 records for Potential Accident Level - V
Pal_V_Sample_Df   = Pal_V.sample(n=113, replace=True)
In [36]:
# Function to actually augment the description data.
def augmentText(pal_df):
    for i, row in pal_df.iterrows():
        pal_df.at[i, 'Description'] = aug_w2v.augment(row['Description'])
In [37]:
# Invoke augmentText function, to augment 93 records for Potential Accident Level - I
augmentText(Pal_I_Sample_Df)

# Invoke augmentText function, to augment 50 records for Potential Accident Level - II
augmentText(Pal_II_Sample_Df)

# Invoke augmentText function, to augment 36 records for Potential Accident Level - III
augmentText(Pal_III_Sample_Df)

# Invoke augmentText function, to augment 113 records for Potential Accident Level - V
augmentText(Pal_V_Sample_Df)
In [38]:
# Concatenating Augmented dataframes.
frames = [df, Pal_I_Sample_Df, Pal_II_Sample_Df, Pal_III_Sample_Df, Pal_V_Sample_Df]
df_bal = pd.concat(frames)

# Shuffling the records in dataframe as they do remain grouped after concatenation.
df_bal = df_bal.sample(frac = 1).reset_index(drop=True)

In [55]:
def clean_text(text):
    text = text.lower()
    
    pattern = re.compile('http[s]?://(?:[a-zA-Z]|[0-9]|[$-_@.&+]|[!*\(\),]|(?:%[0-9a-fA-F][0-9a-fA-F]))+')
    text = pattern.sub('', text)
    text = " ".join(filter(lambda x:x[0]!='@', text.split()))
    emoji = re.compile("["
                           u"\U0001F600-\U0001FFFF"  # emoticons
                           u"\U0001F300-\U0001F5FF"  # symbols & pictographs
                           u"\U0001F680-\U0001F6FF"  # transport & map symbols
                           u"\U0001F1E0-\U0001F1FF"  # flags (iOS)
                           u"\U00002702-\U000027B0"
                           u"\U000024C2-\U0001F251"
                           "]+", flags=re.UNICODE)
    
    text = emoji.sub(r'', text)
    text = text.lower()
    text = re.sub(r"i'm", "i am", text)
    text = re.sub(r"he's", "he is", text)
    text = re.sub(r"she's", "she is", text)
    text = re.sub(r"that's", "that is", text)        
    text = re.sub(r"what's", "what is", text)
    text = re.sub(r"where's", "where is", text) 
    text = re.sub(r"\'ll", " will", text)  
    text = re.sub(r"\'ve", " have", text)  
    text = re.sub(r"\'re", " are", text)
    text = re.sub(r"\'d", " would", text)
    text = re.sub(r"\'ve", " have", text)
    text = re.sub(r"won't", "will not", text)
    text = re.sub(r"don't", "do not", text)
    text = re.sub(r"did't", "did not", text)
    text = re.sub(r"can't", "can not", text)
    text = re.sub(r"it's", "it is", text)
    text = re.sub(r"couldn't", "could not", text)
    text = re.sub(r"have't", "have not", text)
    text = re.sub(r"[,.\"\'!@#$%^&*(){}?/;`~:<>+=-]", "", text)
    return text
In [56]:
def CleanTokenize(df):
    head_lines = list()
    lines = df["Clean_Desc"].values.tolist()

    for line in lines:
        line = clean_text(line)
        # tokenize the text
        tokens = word_tokenize(line)
        # remove puntuations
        table = str.maketrans('', '', string.punctuation)
        stripped = [w.translate(table) for w in tokens]
        # remove non alphabetic characters
        words = [word for word in stripped if word.isalpha()]
        # remove stop words
        words = [w for w in words if not w in stopwords]
        head_lines.append(words)
    return head_lines

In [59]:
# Class which would proivde vectorizers based upon the name ie For CountVectorizer its Count, for TFIDFVectorizer its TFIDF 
# & for Tokenizer its Token
class Vectorizer():
    def __init__(self, vectorName):
        self.vectorName = vectorName
        if (self.vectorName == 'Count'):
            self.vector = CountVectorizer()
        elif (self.vectorName == 'TFIDF'):
            self.vector = TfidfVectorizer()
        elif (self.vectorName == 'Token'):
            self.vector = Tokenizer()
        
    def fit(self, text):
        if (self.vectorName == 'Token'):
            self.vector.fit_on_texts(text)
        else:
            self.vector.fit(text)
        
    def fit_transform(self, text):
        if (self.vectorName != 'Token'):
            return self.vector.fit_transform(text)
            
    def texts_to_sequences(self, text):
        lineText = ''
        if (self.vectorName == 'Token'):
            return self.vector.texts_to_sequences(text)
        else:
            textList = []
            for line in text:
                for l in line:
                    if lineText == '':
                        lineText = l
                    else:
                        lineText = lineText + " " + l
                textList.append(lineText)
            return textList
    
    def uniqueTokens(self):
        if (self.vectorName == 'Token'):
            return self.vector.word_index
        else:
            return self.vector.vocabulary_
    
    def vocabularySize(self):
        return (len(self.uniqueTokens()) + 1)
In [60]:
# Function to get Pad sequences
def getPadSequences(vectorizedWords, maxLen):
    if (type(vectorizedWords) == list):
        linesPad = sequence.pad_sequences(vectorizedWords, maxlen=maxLen, padding='post')
    else:
        linesPad = sequence.pad_sequences(vectorizedWords.toarray(), maxlen=maxLen, padding='post')
    return linesPad

# Function to generate indices & shuffle
def generateIndicesAndShuffle(endRange):
    indices = np.arange(endRange)
    np.random.shuffle(indices)
    return indices
In [62]:
# Function for Train Test Split
def trainTestSplit(split, X, y):
    splitValue  = int(split * X.shape[0])
    
    X_train = X[:-splitValue]
    y_train = y[:-splitValue]
    X_test  = X[-splitValue:]
    y_test  = y[-splitValue:]
    
    return X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test

Build the embedding layer¶

In [74]:
# Method for creating embedding layer using GloVe model
def generateEmbeddingLayer(wordIdx, embeddingDim, embeddingsIdx, maxLen):
    embeddingMtrx = np.zeros((len(wordIdx) + 1, embeddingDim))
    c = 0
    for word, i in wordIdx.items():
        embeddingVtr = embeddingsIdx.get(word)
        if embeddingVtr is not None:
            c+=1
            embeddingMtrx[i] = embeddingVtr
    print(c)
    embeddingLayer = Embedding(len(wordIdx) + 1, embeddingDim, weights=[embeddingMtrx], 
                                input_length=maxLen, trainable=False)
    return embeddingLayer

In [164]:
def accuracy_based_CI(results, ci):
    ci_value = 0
    avg = round(results.mean()*100, 2)
    std = round(results.std()*100, 2)

    if (ci == 99 or ci == 99.73):
        ci_value = 3
    elif (ci == 95 or ci == 95.45):
        ci_value = 2
    else:
        ci_value = 1
        
    CI_min = round((avg - (ci_value * std)), 2)
    CI_max = round((avg + (ci_value * std)), 2)
    return avg, std, CI_min, CI_max
In [165]:
def rightly_identified(actual, predictions):
    a = pd.DataFrame()  # empty dataframe

    for i in np.sort(actual.unique()):
        try:  # because we get a key error if we use value_counts()[i] when the given class i does not exist in the value_count() array
            a.loc[i,'total instances'] = len(actual[actual == i]) # value count of a given class i
            a.loc[i, 'identified right'] = pd.Series(predictions[actual == i]).value_counts()[i] # number of instances where a given class i was identified correctly
            a.loc[i, '%'] = round(100*pd.Series(predictions[actual == i]).value_counts()[i]/len(actual[actual == i]), 1)  # percentage of predictions that were correct for a given class
        except:  # if the key error discussed above occurs, assign the percentage = 0
            a.loc[i, '%'] = 0.0
    return a
In [166]:
def con_matrix(actual, predictions):
    #from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix
    print('Confusion Matrix')
    matrix = pd.DataFrame(confusion_matrix(actual, predictions), columns = np.unique(actual), index = np.unique(actual))
    # confusion_matrix() returns the confusion matrix. Wrapping this matrix in a dataframe with appropriate column names and index
    matrix.loc[:,'total count actual class'] = matrix.sum(axis = 1)  # sum accross the columns
    matrix.loc['total count predicted'] = matrix.sum(axis = 0)  # row sum
    return matrix

Using RandomizedSearchCV with RepeatedStratifiedKFold for Logistic Regression hyper parameter tuning using CountVectorizer¶

In [168]:
k = 10
params = {
            'solver': ['newton-cg', 'lbfgs', 'liblinear'], 
            'penalty': ['l1', 'l2'], 
            'C': [200, 100, 10, 1.0, 0.1, 0.01, 0.001, 0.0001],
            'dual': [True, False],
            'multi_class': ['auto', 'ovr', 'multinomial']
         }

logregModelCtVtr = LogisticRegression()
rskfRscvCtVtr = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
logRscvCtVtr = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=logregModelCtVtr, param_distributions=params, cv=rskfRscvCtVtr, verbose =2, 
                              n_iter=10, n_jobs=-1, error_score=0)

logRscvCtVtr = logRscvCtVtr.fit(X_trainCnt, y_trainCnt)

maxStdScoreCtVtr = 0.0
maxMeanScoreCtVtr = logRscvCtVtr.best_score_
means = logRscvCtVtr.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = logRscvCtVtr.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = logRscvCtVtr.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    if (maxMeanScoreCtVtr == mean):
        maxStdScoreCtVtr = stdev

print('Best score & parameters using RandomizedSearchCV: {} ({}) using {}'.format(round((maxMeanScoreCtVtr * 100), 2), round((maxStdScoreCtVtr * 100), 2), logRscvCtVtr.best_params_))

Finding Accuracy for Logistic Regression model (CountVectorizer) using tuned parameters.¶¶

In [169]:
k = 10
best_rscv_solver = logRscvCtVtr.best_params_['solver']
best_rscv_penalty = logRscvCtVtr.best_params_['penalty']
best_rscv_multi_class = logRscvCtVtr.best_params_['multi_class']
best_rscv_dual = logRscvCtVtr.best_params_['dual']
best_rscv_C = logRscvCtVtr.best_params_['C']

logregModelCtVtr = LogisticRegression(solver=best_rscv_solver, penalty=best_rscv_penalty, multi_class=best_rscv_multi_class, 
                                  dual=best_rscv_dual, C=best_rscv_C)
rskf = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
rskf_results = cross_val_score(logregModelCtVtr, X_trainCnt, y_trainCnt, cv=rskf)
rskf_mean, rskf_std, rskf_CI_min, rskf_CI_max = accuracy_based_CI(rskf_results, 95)

print('{}% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(rskf_mean))
print('{} is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(rskf_std))
print('There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between {} & {}'.format(rskf_CI_min, rskf_CI_max))

20.66% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
4.89 is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 10.88 & 30.44

Observation:-¶

  • We are getting an average accuracy of almost 20.66%.
  • There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 10.88% & 30.44% ie there is 5% chance that the accuracy of this model would greater than the maximum accuracy or lesser than the minimum accuracy.

Using RandomizedSearchCV with RepeatedStratifiedKFold for Logistic Regression hyper parameter tuning using TF-IDFVectorizer¶

In [170]:
k = 10
params = {
            'solver': ['newton-cg', 'lbfgs', 'liblinear'], 
            'penalty': ['l1', 'l2'], 
            'C': [200, 100, 10, 1.0, 0.1, 0.01, 0.001, 0.0001],
            'dual': [True, False],
            'multi_class': ['auto', 'ovr', 'multinomial']
         }

logregModelTfidfVtr = LogisticRegression()
rskfRscvTfidfVtr = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
logRscvTfidfVtr = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=logregModelTfidfVtr, param_distributions=params, 
                                     cv=rskfRscvTfidfVtr, verbose =2, n_iter=10, n_jobs=-1, error_score=0)

logRscvTfidfVtr = logRscvTfidfVtr.fit(X_trainTfidf, y_trainTfidf)

maxStdScoreTfidfVtr = 0.0
maxMeanScoreTfidfVtr = logRscvTfidfVtr.best_score_
means = logRscvTfidfVtr.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = logRscvTfidfVtr.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = logRscvTfidfVtr.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    if (maxMeanScoreTfidfVtr == mean):
        maxStdScoreTfidfVtr = stdev

print('Best score & parameters using RandomizedSearchCV: {} ({}) using {}'.format(round((maxMeanScoreTfidfVtr * 100), 2), round((maxStdScoreTfidfVtr * 100), 2), logRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_))

Fitting 30 folds for each of 10 candidates, totalling 300 fits

Finding Accuracy for Logistic Regression model (TF-IDFVectorizer) using tuned parameters.¶¶

In [171]:
k = 10
best_rscv_solver = logRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_['solver']
best_rscv_penalty = logRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_['penalty']
best_rscv_multi_class = logRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_['multi_class']
best_rscv_dual = logRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_['dual']
best_rscv_C = logRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_['C']

logregModelTfidfVtr = LogisticRegression(solver=best_rscv_solver, penalty=best_rscv_penalty, 
                                         multi_class=best_rscv_multi_class, dual=best_rscv_dual, C=best_rscv_C)
rskf = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
rskf_results = cross_val_score(logregModelTfidfVtr, X_trainTfidf, y_trainTfidf, cv=rskf)
rskf_mean, rskf_std, rskf_CI_min, rskf_CI_max = accuracy_based_CI(rskf_results, 95)

print('{}% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(rskf_mean))
print('{} is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(rskf_std))
print('There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between {} & {}'.format(rskf_CI_min, rskf_CI_max))

20.71% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
0.88 is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 18.95 & 22.47

Observation:-¶

  • We are getting an average accuracy of almost 20.71%.
  • There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 18.95% & 22.47% ie there is 5% chance that the accuracy of this model would greater than the maximum accuracy or lesser than the minimum accuracy.

Using RandomizedSearchCV with RepeatedStratifiedKFold for Logistic Regression hyper parameter tuning using Tokenizer¶

In [172]:
k = 10
params = {
            'solver': ['newton-cg', 'lbfgs', 'liblinear'], 
            'penalty': ['l1', 'l2'], 
            'C': [200, 100, 10, 1.0, 0.1, 0.01, 0.001, 0.0001],
            'dual': [True, False],
            'multi_class': ['auto', 'ovr', 'multinomial']
         }

logregModelTkn = LogisticRegression()
rskfRscvTkn = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
logRscvTkn = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=logregModelTkn, param_distributions=params, cv=rskfRscvTkn, 
                                verbose =2, n_iter=10, n_jobs=-1, error_score=0)

logRscvTkn = logRscvTkn.fit(X_trainToken, y_trainToken)

maxStdScoreTkn = 0.0
maxMeanScoreTkn = logRscvTkn.best_score_
means = logRscvTkn.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = logRscvTkn.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = logRscvTkn.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    if (maxMeanScoreTkn == mean):
        maxStdScoreTkn = stdev

print('Best score & parameters using RandomizedSearchCV: {} ({}) using {}'.format(round((maxMeanScoreTkn * 100), 2), round((maxStdScoreTkn * 100), 2), logRscvTkn.best_params_))

Fitting 30 folds for each of 10 candidates, totalling 300 fits

Finding Accuracy for Logistic Regression model (Tokenizer) using tuned parameters.¶¶

k = 10
best_rscv_solver = logRscvTkn.best_params_['solver']
best_rscv_penalty = logRscvTkn.best_params_['penalty']
best_rscv_multi_class = logRscvTkn.best_params_['multi_class']
best_rscv_dual = logRscvTkn.best_params_['dual']
best_rscv_C = logRscvTkn.best_params_['C']

logregModelTkn = LogisticRegression(solver=best_rscv_solver, penalty=best_rscv_penalty, multi_class=best_rscv_multi_class, 
                                  dual=best_rscv_dual, C=best_rscv_C)
rskf = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
rskf_results = cross_val_score(logregModelTkn, X_trainToken, y_trainToken, cv=rskf)
rskf_mean, rskf_std, rskf_CI_min, rskf_CI_max = accuracy_based_CI(rskf_results, 95)

print('{}% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(rskf_mean))
print('{} is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(rskf_std))
print('There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between {} & {}'.format(rskf_CI_min, rskf_CI_max))

36.8% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
6.25 is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 24.3 & 49.3

Observation:-¶

  • We are getting an average accuracy of almost 36.8%.
  • There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 24.3% & 49.3% ie there is 5% chance that the accuracy of this model would greater than the maximum accuracy or lesser than the minimum accuracy.

# check the accuracy on the test set
accuracy_logregCntVtr = round(logregModelCtVtr.score(X_testCnt, y_testCnt), 2) * 100
print('Accuracy on the test set (using Count Vectorizer) {}%'.format(accuracy_logregCntVtr))

logregModelTfidfVtr.fit(X_trainTfidf, y_trainTfidf)
predTfidfVtr = logregModelTfidfVtr.predict(X_testTfidf)

# check the accuracy on the training set
print('Accuracy on the train set (using TF-IDF Vectorizer) {}%'.format(logregModelTfidfVtr.score(X_trainTfidf, y_trainTfidf) * 100))
# check the accuracy on the test set
accuracy_logregTfidfVtr = round(logregModelTfidfVtr.score(X_testTfidf, y_testTfidf), 2) * 100
print('Accuracy on the test set (using TF-IDF Vectorizer) {}%'.format(accuracy_logregTfidfVtr))

logregModelTkn.fit(X_trainToken, y_trainToken)
predTkn = logregModelTkn.predict(X_testToken)

# check the accuracy on the training set
print('Accuracy on the train set (using Tokenizer) {}%'.format(logregModelTkn.score(X_trainToken, y_trainToken) * 100))
# check the accuracy on the test set
accuracy_logregTkn = round(logregModelTkn.score(X_testToken, y_testToken), 2) * 100
print('Accuracy on the test set (using Tokenizer) {}%'.format(accuracy_logregTkn))

Accuracy on the train set (using Count Vectorizer) 35.2589641434263%
Accuracy on the test set (using Count Vectorizer) 20.0%
Accuracy on the train set (using TF-IDF Vectorizer) 20.717131474103585%
Accuracy on the test set (using TF-IDF Vectorizer) 18.0%
Accuracy on the train set (using Tokenizer) 59.76095617529881%
Accuracy on the test set (using Tokenizer) 39.0%

Observation:-¶

  • For Logistic Regression, training model is overfitted when Tokenizer is used.
  • The training accuracy is higher than testing accuracy.

Naive Bayes¶

Using RandomizedSearchCV with RepeatedStratifiedKFold for Navie Bayes hyper parameter tuning using Count Vectorizer¶

In [181]:
k = 10
params = {
            'alpha': np.linspace(0.5, 1.5, 6),
            'fit_prior': [True, False]
         }

nbMultiModelCntVtr = MultinomialNB()
rskfRscvCtVtr = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
nbRscvCntVtr = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=nbMultiModelCntVtr, param_distributions=params, 
                             cv=rskfRscvCtVtr, verbose =2, n_iter=10, n_jobs=-1, error_score=0)

nbRscvCntVtr = nbRscvCntVtr.fit(X_trainCnt, y_trainCnt)

max_std_score = 0.0
max_mean_score = nbRscvCntVtr.best_score_
means = nbRscvCntVtr.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = nbRscvCntVtr.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = nbRscvCntVtr.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    if (max_mean_score == mean):
        max_std_score = stdev

print('Best score & parameters using RandomizedSearchCV: {} ({}) using {}'.format(round((max_mean_score * 100), 2), round((max_std_score * 100), 2), nbRscvCntVtr.best_params_))

Fitting 30 folds for each of 10 candidates, totalling 300 fits
Best score & parameters using RandomizedSearchCV: 23.63 (4.57) using {'fit_prior': True, 'alpha': 1.3}

Finding Accuracy for Navie Bayes model (Count Vectorizer) using tuned parameters.¶

In [182]:
best_rscv_alpha = nbRscvCntVtr.best_params_['alpha']
best_rscv_fit_prior = nbRscvCntVtr.best_params_['fit_prior']

k = 10
nbMultiModelCntVtr = MultinomialNB(alpha=best_rscv_alpha, fit_prior=best_rscv_fit_prior)
nb_rskf = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
nb_rskf_results = cross_val_score(nbMultiModelCntVtr, X_trainCnt, y_trainCnt, cv=nb_rskf)
nb_rskf_mean, nb_rskf_std, nb_rskf_CI_min, nb_rskf_CI_max = accuracy_based_CI(nb_rskf_results, 95)

print('{}% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(nb_rskf_mean))
print('{} is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(nb_rskf_std))
print('There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between {} & {}'.format(nb_rskf_CI_min, nb_rskf_CI_max))

22.11% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
3.4 is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 15.31 & 28.91

Observation:-¶

  • We are getting an average accuracy of almost 22.11%.
  • There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 15.31% & 28.91% ie there is 5% chance that the accuracy of this model would greater than the maximum accuracy or lesser than the minimum accuracy.

Using RandomizedSearchCV with RepeatedStratifiedKFold for Navie Bayes hyper parameter tuning using TF-IDF Vectorizer¶

In [183]:
k = 10
params = {
            'alpha': np.linspace(0.5, 1.5, 6),
            'fit_prior': [True, False]
         }

nbMultiModelTfidfVtr = MultinomialNB()
rskfRscvTfidfVtr = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
nbRscvTfidfVtr = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=nbMultiModelTfidfVtr, param_distributions=params, 
                             cv=rskfRscvTfidfVtr, verbose =2, n_iter=10, n_jobs=-1, error_score=0)

nbRscvTfidfVtr = nbRscvTfidfVtr.fit(X_trainTfidf, y_trainTfidf)

max_std_score = 0.0
max_mean_score = nbRscvTfidfVtr.best_score_
means = nbRscvTfidfVtr.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = nbRscvTfidfVtr.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = nbRscvTfidfVtr.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    if (max_mean_score == mean):
        max_std_score = stdev

print('Best score & parameters using RandomizedSearchCV: {} ({}) using {}'.format(round((max_mean_score * 100), 2), round((max_std_score * 100), 2), nbRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_))

Fitting 30 folds for each of 10 candidates, totalling 300 fits

Finding Accuracy for Navie Bayes model (TF-IDF Vectorizer) using tuned parameters.¶

In [184]:
best_rscv_alpha = nbRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_['alpha']
best_rscv_fit_prior = nbRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_['fit_prior']

k = 10
nbMultiModelTfidfVtr = MultinomialNB(alpha=best_rscv_alpha, fit_prior=best_rscv_fit_prior)
nb_rskf = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
nb_rskf_results = cross_val_score(nbMultiModelCntVtr, X_trainTfidf, y_trainTfidf, cv=nb_rskf)
nb_rskf_mean, nb_rskf_std, nb_rskf_CI_min, nb_rskf_CI_max = accuracy_based_CI(nb_rskf_results, 95)

print('{}% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(nb_rskf_mean))
print('{} is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(nb_rskf_std))
print('There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between {} & {}'.format(nb_rskf_CI_min, nb_rskf_CI_max))

20.71% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
0.88 is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 18.95 & 22.47

Observation:-¶

  • We are getting an average accuracy of almost 20.71%.
  • There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 18.95% & 22.47% ie there is 5% chance that the accuracy of this model would greater than the maximum accuracy or lesser than the minimum accuracy.

Using RandomizedSearchCV with RepeatedStratifiedKFold for Navie Bayes hyper parameter tuning using Tokenizer¶

In [185]:
k = 10
params = {
            'alpha': np.linspace(0.5, 1.5, 6),
            'fit_prior': [True, False]
         }

nbMultiModelTkn = MultinomialNB()
rskfRscvTkn = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
nbRscvTkn = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=nbMultiModelTkn, param_distributions=params, 
                             cv=rskfRscvTkn, verbose =2, n_iter=10, n_jobs=-1, error_score=0)

nbRscvTkn = nbRscvTkn.fit(X_trainToken, y_trainToken)

max_std_score = 0.0
max_mean_score = nbRscvTfidfVtr.best_score_
means = nbRscvTkn.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = nbRscvTkn.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = nbRscvTkn.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    if (max_mean_score == mean):
        max_std_score = stdev

print('Best score & parameters using RandomizedSearchCV: {} ({}) using {}'.format(round((max_mean_score * 100), 2), round((max_std_score * 100), 2), nbRscvTkn.best_params_))

Fitting 30 folds for each of 10 candidates, totalling 300 fits

best_rscv_fit_prior = nbRscvTkn.best_params_['fit_prior']

k = 10
nbMultiModelTkn = MultinomialNB(alpha=best_rscv_alpha, fit_prior=best_rscv_fit_prior)
nb_rskf = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
nb_rskf_results = cross_val_score(nbMultiModelTkn, X_trainToken, y_trainToken, cv=nb_rskf)
nb_rskf_mean, nb_rskf_std, nb_rskf_CI_min, nb_rskf_CI_max = accuracy_based_CI(nb_rskf_results, 95)

print('{}% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(nb_rskf_mean))
print('{} is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(nb_rskf_std))
print('There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between {} & {}'.format(nb_rskf_CI_min, nb_rskf_CI_max))

34.94% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
6.8 is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 21.34 & 48.54

Observation:-¶

  • We are getting an average accuracy of almost 34.94%.
  • There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 21.34% & 48.54% ie there is 5% chance that the accuracy of this model would greater than the maximum accuracy or lesser than the minimum accuracy.

Random Forest Classifier¶

Using RandomizedSearchCV with RepeatedStratifiedKFold for RandomForestClassifier hyper parameter tuning using Count Vectorizer¶

In [194]:
k = 10
params = {
            'bootstrap': [True, False],
            'max_depth': [10, 20, 30, 40, 50],
            'max_features': ['auto', 'sqrt'],
            'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4, 8],
            'n_estimators': [100]
         }

rfcModelCntVtr = RandomForestClassifier()
rskf_rscv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
rfcRscvCntVtr = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=rfcModelCntVtr, param_distributions=params, 
                              cv=rskf_rscv, verbose =2, n_iter=10, n_jobs=-1, error_score=0)

rfcRscvCntVtr = rfcRscvCntVtr.fit(X_trainCnt, y_trainCnt)

max_std_score = 0.0
max_mean_score = rfcRscvCntVtr.best_score_
means = rfcRscvCntVtr.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = rfcRscvCntVtr.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = rfcRscvCntVtr.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    if (max_mean_score == mean):
        max_std_score = stdev

print('Best score & parameters using RandomizedSearchCV: {} ({}) using {}'.format(round((max_mean_score * 100), 2), round((max_std_score * 100), 2), rfcRscvCntVtr.best_params_))

Finding Accuracy for RandomForestClassifier model (Count Vectorizer) using tuned parameters.¶

In [195]:
best_rscv_bootstrap = rfcRscvCntVtr.best_params_['bootstrap']
best_rscv_max_depth = rfcRscvCntVtr.best_params_['max_depth']
best_rscv_max_features = rfcRscvCntVtr.best_params_['max_features']
best_rscv_min_samples_leaf = rfcRscvCntVtr.best_params_['min_samples_leaf']
best_rscv_n_estimators = rfcRscvCntVtr.best_params_['n_estimators']

k = 10
rfcRscvCntVtr = RandomForestClassifier(bootstrap=best_rscv_bootstrap, max_depth=best_rscv_max_depth, 
                                max_features=best_rscv_max_features, min_samples_leaf=best_rscv_min_samples_leaf, 
                                n_estimators=best_rscv_n_estimators)
rfc_rskf = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
rfc_rskf_results = cross_val_score(rfcRscvCntVtr, X_trainCnt, y_trainCnt, cv=rfc_rskf)
rfc_rskf_mean, rfc_rskf_std, rfc_rskf_CI_min, rfc_rskf_CI_max = accuracy_based_CI(rfc_rskf_results, 95)

print('{}% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(rfc_rskf_mean))
print('{} is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(rfc_rskf_std))
print('There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between {} & {}'.format(rfc_rskf_CI_min, rfc_rskf_CI_max))

25.24% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
6.08 is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 13.08 & 37.4

Observation:-¶

  • We are getting an average accuracy of almost 25.24%.
  • There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 13.08% & 37.4% ie there is 5% chance that the accuracy of this model would greater than the maximum accuracy or lesser than the minimum accuracy.

Using RandomizedSearchCV with RepeatedStratifiedKFold for RandomForestClassifier hyper parameter tuning using TF-IDF Vectorizer¶

In [196]:
k = 10
params = {
            'bootstrap': [True, False],
            'max_depth': [10, 20, 30, 40, 50],
            'max_features': ['auto', 'sqrt'],
            'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4, 8],
            'n_estimators': [100]
         }

rfcModelTfidfVtr = RandomForestClassifier()
rskf_rscv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
rfcRscvTfidfVtr = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=rfcModelTfidfVtr, param_distributions=params, cv=rskf_rscv, 
                              verbose =2, n_iter=10, n_jobs=-1, error_score=0)

rfcRscvTfidfVtr = rfcRscvTfidfVtr.fit(X_trainTfidf, y_trainTfidf)

max_std_score = 0.0
max_mean_score = rfcRscvTfidfVtr.best_score_
means = rfcRscvTfidfVtr.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = rfcRscvTfidfVtr.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = rfcRscvTfidfVtr.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    if (max_mean_score == mean):
        max_std_score = stdev

print('Best score & parameters using RandomizedSearchCV: {} ({}) using {}'.format(round((max_mean_score * 100), 2), round((max_std_score * 100), 2), rfcRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_))

Fitting 30 folds for each of 10 candidates, totalling 300 fits

Finding Accuracy for RandomForestClassifier model (TF-IDF Vectorizer) using tuned parameters.¶

In [197]:
best_rscv_bootstrap = rfcRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_['bootstrap']
best_rscv_max_depth = rfcRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_['max_depth']
best_rscv_max_features = rfcRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_['max_features']
best_rscv_min_samples_leaf = rfcRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_['min_samples_leaf']
best_rscv_n_estimators = rfcRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_['n_estimators']

k = 10
rfcModelTfidfVtr = RandomForestClassifier(bootstrap=best_rscv_bootstrap, max_depth=best_rscv_max_depth, 
                                                     max_features=best_rscv_max_features, 
                                                     min_samples_leaf=best_rscv_min_samples_leaf, 
                                                     n_estimators=best_rscv_n_estimators)
rfc_rskf = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
rfc_rskf_results = cross_val_score(rfcModelTfidfVtr, X_trainTfidf, y_trainTfidf, cv=rfc_rskf)
rfc_rskf_mean, rfc_rskf_std, rfc_rskf_CI_min, rfc_rskf_CI_max = accuracy_based_CI(rfc_rskf_results, 95)

print('{}% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(rfc_rskf_mean))
print('{} is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(rfc_rskf_std))
print('There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between {} & {}'.format(rfc_rskf_CI_min, rfc_rskf_CI_max))

20.71% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
0.88 is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 18.95 & 22.47

Observation:-¶

  • We are getting an average accuracy of almost 20.71%.
  • There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 18.95% & 22.47% ie there is 5% chance that the accuracy of this model would greater than the maximum accuracy or lesser than the minimum accuracy.

Using RandomizedSearchCV with RepeatedStratifiedKFold for RandomForestClassifier hyper parameter tuning using Tokenizer¶

In [198]:
k = 10
params = {
            'bootstrap': [True, False],
            'max_depth': [10, 20, 30, 40, 50],
            'max_features': ['auto', 'sqrt'],
            'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 4, 8],
            'n_estimators': [100]
         }

rfcModelTkn = RandomForestClassifier()
rskf_rscv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
rfcRscvTkn = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=rfcModelTkn, param_distributions=params, 
                              cv=rskf_rscv, verbose =2, n_iter=10, n_jobs=-1, error_score=0)

rfcRscvTkn = rfcRscvTkn.fit(X_trainToken, y_trainToken)

max_std_score = 0.0
max_mean_score = rfcRscvTkn.best_score_
means = rfcRscvTkn.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = rfcRscvTkn.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = rfcRscvTkn.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    if (max_mean_score == mean):
        max_std_score = stdev

print('Best score & parameters using RandomizedSearchCV: {} ({}) using {}'.format(round((max_mean_score * 100), 2), round((max_std_score * 100), 2), rfcRscvTkn.best_params_))

Fitting 30 folds for each of 10 candidates, totalling 300 fits

Finding Accuracy for RandomForestClassifier model (Tokenizer) using tuned parameters.¶

In [199]:
best_rscv_bootstrap = rfcRscvTkn.best_params_['bootstrap']
best_rscv_max_depth = rfcRscvTkn.best_params_['max_depth']
best_rscv_max_features = rfcRscvTkn.best_params_['max_features']
best_rscv_min_samples_leaf = rfcRscvTkn.best_params_['min_samples_leaf']
best_rscv_n_estimators = rfcRscvTkn.best_params_['n_estimators']

k = 10
rfcModelTkn = RandomForestClassifier(bootstrap=best_rscv_bootstrap, max_depth=best_rscv_max_depth, 
                                    max_features=best_rscv_max_features, min_samples_leaf=best_rscv_min_samples_leaf, 
                                    n_estimators=best_rscv_n_estimators)
rfc_rskf = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
rfc_rskf_results = cross_val_score(rfcModelTkn, X_trainToken, y_trainToken, cv=rfc_rskf)
rfc_rskf_mean, rfc_rskf_std, rfc_rskf_CI_min, rfc_rskf_CI_max = accuracy_based_CI(rfc_rskf_results, 95)

print('{}% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(rfc_rskf_mean))
print('{} is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(rfc_rskf_std))
print('There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between {} & {}'.format(rfc_rskf_CI_min, rfc_rskf_CI_max))

57.57% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
6.83 is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 43.91 & 71.23

Observation:-¶

  • We are getting an average accuracy of almost 57.57%.
  • There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 43.91% & 71.23% ie there is 5% chance that the accuracy of this model would greater than the maximum accuracy or lesser than the minimum accuracy.

rfcModelCntVtr.fit(X_trainCnt, y_trainCnt)

Accuracy on the test set (using TF-IDF Vectorizer) 18.0%
Accuracy on the train set (using Tokenizer) 99.800796812749%
Accuracy on the test set (using Tokenizer) 63.0%

Observation:-¶

  • The model trained, using Random Forest Classifier, on training data is overfitted. This is the case when we are using Count vectorizer & Tokenizer.
  • The training accuracy, using Random Forest Classifier, is way little higher than testing accuracy in case of TF-IDF vectorizer.

Support Vector Classifier (SVC)¶

Using RandomizedSearchCV with RepeatedStratifiedKFold for Support Vector Classifier (SVC) hyper parameter tuning using Count Vectorizer¶

In [207]:
k = 10
params = {
            'kernel': ['poly', 'rbf', 'sigmoid'], 
            'C': [1000, 100, 50, 10, 1.0, 0.1, 0.01], 
            'gamma': ['scale', 'auto']
         }

SVCModelCntVtr = SVC()
rskf_rscv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
SVCRscvCntVtr = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=SVCModelCntVtr, param_distributions=params, cv=rskf_rscv, verbose =2, 
                              n_iter=10, n_jobs=-1, error_score=0)

SVCRscvCntVtr = SVCRscvCntVtr.fit(X_trainCnt, y_trainCnt)

max_std_score = 0.0
max_mean_score = SVCRscvCntVtr.best_score_
means = SVCRscvCntVtr.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = SVCRscvCntVtr.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = SVCRscvCntVtr.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    if (max_mean_score == mean):
        max_std_score = stdev

print('Best score & parameters using RandomizedSearchCV: {} ({}) using {}'.format(round((max_mean_score * 100), 2), round((max_std_score * 100), 2), SVCRscvCntVtr.best_params_))

Finding Accuracy for SVC model (Count Vectorizer) using tuned parameters.¶

In [208]:
best_rscv_kernel = SVCRscvCntVtr.best_params_['kernel']
best_rscv_C = SVCRscvCntVtr.best_params_['C']
best_rscv_gamma = SVCRscvCntVtr.best_params_['gamma']

k = 10
SVCModelCntVtr = SVC(kernel=best_rscv_kernel, C=best_rscv_C, gamma=best_rscv_gamma)
SVC_rskf = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
SVC_rskf_results = cross_val_score(SVCModelCntVtr, X_trainCnt, y_trainCnt, cv=SVC_rskf)
SVC_rskf_mean, SVC_rskf_std, SVC_rskf_CI_min, SVC_rskf_CI_max = accuracy_based_CI(SVC_rskf_results, 95)

print('{}% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(SVC_rskf_mean))
print('{} is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(SVC_rskf_std))
print('There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between {} & {}'.format(SVC_rskf_CI_min, SVC_rskf_CI_max))

23.83% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
6.97 is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 9.89 & 37.77

Observation:-¶

  • We are getting an average accuracy of almost 23.83%.
  • There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 9.89% & 37.77% ie there is 5% chance that the accuracy of this model would greater than the maximum accuracy or lesser than the minimum accuracy.

Using RandomizedSearchCV with RepeatedStratifiedKFold for Support Vector Classifier (SVC) hyper parameter tuning using TF-IDF Vectorizer¶

In [209]:
k = 10
params = {
            'kernel': ['poly', 'rbf', 'sigmoid'], 
            'C': [1000, 100, 50, 10, 1.0, 0.1, 0.01], 
            'gamma': ['scale', 'auto']
         }

SVCModelTfidfVtr = SVC()
rskf_rscv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
SVCRscvTfidfVtr = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=SVCModelTfidfVtr, param_distributions=params, cv=rskf_rscv, 
                              verbose =2, n_iter=10, n_jobs=-1, error_score=0)

SVCRscvTfidfVtr = SVCRscvTfidfVtr.fit(X_trainTfidf, y_trainTfidf)

max_std_score = 0.0
max_mean_score = SVCRscvTfidfVtr.best_score_
means = SVCRscvTfidfVtr.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = SVCRscvTfidfVtr.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = SVCRscvTfidfVtr.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    if (max_mean_score == mean):
        max_std_score = stdev

print('Best score & parameters using RandomizedSearchCV: {} ({}) using {}'.format(round((max_mean_score * 100), 2), round((max_std_score * 100), 2), SVCRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_))

Fitting 30 folds for each of 10 candidates, totalling 300 fits
Best score & parameters using RandomizedSearchCV: 20.71 (0.88) using {'kernel': 'sigmoid', 'gamma': 'auto', 'C': 0.1}

best_rscv_kernel = SVCRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_['kernel']

k = 10

SVC_rskf = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
SVC_rskf_results = cross_val_score(SVCModelTfidfVtr, X_trainTfidf, y_trainTfidf, cv=SVC_rskf)
SVC_rskf_mean, SVC_rskf_std, SVC_rskf_CI_min, SVC_rskf_CI_max = accuracy_based_CI(SVC_rskf_results, 95)

print('{}% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(SVC_rskf_mean))

print('There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between {} & {}'.format(SVC_rskf_CI_min, SVC_rskf_CI_max))

K-Nearest Neighbor (KNN)¶

Using RandomizedSearchCV with RepeatedStratifiedKFold for K-Nearest Neighbor (KNN) hyper parameter tuning using Count Vectorizer¶

In [220]:
n_neighbors = list(range(1, 21, 2))
k = 10
params = {
            'n_neighbors': n_neighbors, 
            'weights': ['uniform', 'distance'], 
            'metric': ['euclidean', 'manhattan', 'minkowski'],
            'algorithm': ['auto', 'ball_tree', 'kd_tree', 'brute']
         }

KNNModelCntVtr = KNeighborsClassifier()
rskf_rscv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
knnRscvCntVtr = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=KNNModelCntVtr, param_distributions=params, 
                              cv=rskf_rscv, verbose =2, n_iter=10, n_jobs=-1, error_score=0)

knnRscvCntVtr = knnRscvCntVtr.fit(X_trainCnt, y_trainCnt)

max_std_score = 0.0
max_mean_score = knnRscvCntVtr.best_score_
means = knnRscvCntVtr.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = knnRscvCntVtr.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = knnRscvCntVtr.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    if (max_mean_score == mean):
        max_std_score = stdev

print('Best score & parameters using RandomizedSearchCV: {} ({}) using {}'.format(round((max_mean_score * 100), 2), round((max_std_score * 100), 2), knnRscvCntVtr.best_params_))

Finding Accuracy for KNN model (Count Vectorizer) using tuned parameters.¶

In [221]:
best_rscv_n_neighbors = knnRscvCntVtr.best_params_['n_neighbors']
best_rscv_weights = knnRscvCntVtr.best_params_['weights']
best_rscv_metric = knnRscvCntVtr.best_params_['metric']
best_rscv_algorithm = knnRscvCntVtr.best_params_['algorithm']

k = 10
KNNModelCntVtr = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=best_rscv_n_neighbors, weights=best_rscv_weights, 
                                      metric=best_rscv_metric, algorithm=best_rscv_algorithm)
knn_rskf = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
knn_rskf_results = cross_val_score(KNNModelCntVtr, X_trainCnt, y_trainCnt, cv=knn_rskf)
knn_rskf_mean, knn_rskf_std, knn_rskf_CI_min, knn_rskf_CI_max = accuracy_based_CI(knn_rskf_results, 95)

print('{}% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(knn_rskf_mean))
print('{} is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(knn_rskf_std))
print('There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between {} & {}'.format(knn_rskf_CI_min, knn_rskf_CI_max))

23.44% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
5.61 is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 12.22 & 34.66

Observation:-¶

  • We are getting an average accuracy of almost 23.44%.
  • There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 12.22% & 34.66% ie there is 5% chance that the accuracy of this model would greater than the maximum accuracy or lesser than the minimum accuracy.

Using RandomizedSearchCV with RepeatedStratifiedKFold for K-Nearest Neighbor (KNN) hyper parameter tuning using TF-IDF Vectorizer¶

In [222]:
n_neighbors = list(range(1, 21, 2))
k = 10
params = {
            'n_neighbors': n_neighbors, 
            'weights': ['uniform', 'distance'], 
            'metric': ['euclidean', 'manhattan', 'minkowski'],
            'algorithm': ['auto', 'ball_tree', 'kd_tree', 'brute']
         }

KNNModelTfidfVtr = KNeighborsClassifier()
rskf_rscv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
knnRscvTfidfVtr = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=KNNModelTfidfVtr, param_distributions=params, 
                              cv=rskf_rscv, verbose =2, n_iter=10, n_jobs=-1, error_score=0)

knnRscvTfidfVtr = knnRscvTfidfVtr.fit(X_trainTfidf, y_trainTfidf)

max_std_score = 0.0
max_mean_score = knnRscvTfidfVtr.best_score_
means = knnRscvTfidfVtr.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = knnRscvTfidfVtr.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = knnRscvTfidfVtr.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    if (max_mean_score == mean):
        max_std_score = stdev

print('Best score & parameters using RandomizedSearchCV: {} ({}) using {}'.format(round((max_mean_score * 100), 2), round((max_std_score * 100), 2), knnRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_))

Fitting 30 folds for each of 10 candidates, totalling 300 fits

Finding Accuracy for KNN model (TF-IDF Vectorizer) using tuned parameters.¶

In [223]:
best_rscv_n_neighbors = knnRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_['n_neighbors']
best_rscv_weights = knnRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_['weights']
best_rscv_metric = knnRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_['metric']
best_rscv_algorithm = knnRscvTfidfVtr.best_params_['algorithm']

k = 10
KNNModelTfidfVtr = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=best_rscv_n_neighbors, weights=best_rscv_weights, 
                                        metric=best_rscv_metric, algorithm=best_rscv_algorithm)
knn_rskf = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
knn_rskf_results = cross_val_score(KNNModelTfidfVtr, X_trainTfidf, y_trainTfidf, cv=knn_rskf)
knn_rskf_mean, knn_rskf_std, knn_rskf_CI_min, knn_rskf_CI_max = accuracy_based_CI(knn_rskf_results, 95)

print('{}% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(knn_rskf_mean))
print('{} is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(knn_rskf_std))
print('There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between {} & {}'.format(knn_rskf_CI_min, knn_rskf_CI_max))

20.85% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
0.92 is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 19.01 & 22.69

Observation:-¶

  • We are getting an average accuracy of almost 20.85%.
  • There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 19.01% & 22.69% ie there is 5% chance that the accuracy of this model would greater than the maximum accuracy or lesser than the minimum accuracy.

Using RandomizedSearchCV with RepeatedStratifiedKFold for K-Nearest Neighbor (KNN) hyper parameter tuning using Tokenizer¶

In [224]:
n_neighbors = list(range(1, 21, 2))
k = 10
params = {
            'n_neighbors': n_neighbors, 
            'weights': ['uniform', 'distance'], 
            'metric': ['euclidean', 'manhattan', 'minkowski'],
            'algorithm': ['auto', 'ball_tree', 'kd_tree', 'brute']
         }

KNNModelTkn = KNeighborsClassifier()
rskf_rscv = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
knnRscvTkn = RandomizedSearchCV(estimator=KNNModelTkn, param_distributions=params, 
                              cv=rskf_rscv, verbose =2, n_iter=10, n_jobs=-1, error_score=0)

knnRscvTkn = knnRscvTkn.fit(X_trainToken, y_trainToken)

max_std_score = 0.0
max_mean_score = knnRscvTkn.best_score_
means = knnRscvTkn.cv_results_['mean_test_score']
stds = knnRscvTkn.cv_results_['std_test_score']
params = knnRscvTkn.cv_results_['params']
for mean, stdev, param in zip(means, stds, params):
    if (max_mean_score == mean):
        max_std_score = stdev

print('Best score & parameters using RandomizedSearchCV: {} ({}) using {}'.format(round((max_mean_score * 100), 2), round((max_std_score * 100), 2), knnRscvTkn.best_params_))

Fitting 30 folds for each of 10 candidates, totalling 300 fits

Finding Accuracy for KNN model (Tokenizer) using tuned parameters.¶

In [225]:
best_rscv_n_neighbors = knnRscvTkn.best_params_['n_neighbors']
best_rscv_weights = knnRscvTkn.best_params_['weights']
best_rscv_metric = knnRscvTkn.best_params_['metric']
best_rscv_algorithm = knnRscvTkn.best_params_['algorithm']

k = 10
KNNModelTkn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=best_rscv_n_neighbors, weights=best_rscv_weights, 
                                   metric=best_rscv_metric, algorithm=best_rscv_algorithm)
knn_rskf = RepeatedStratifiedKFold(n_splits=k, n_repeats=3)
knn_rskf_results = cross_val_score(KNNModelTkn, X_trainToken, y_trainToken, cv=knn_rskf)
knn_rskf_mean, knn_rskf_std, knn_rskf_CI_min, knn_rskf_CI_max = accuracy_based_CI(knn_rskf_results, 95)

print('{}% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(knn_rskf_mean))
print('{} is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.'.format(knn_rskf_std))
print('There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between {} & {}'.format(knn_rskf_CI_min, knn_rskf_CI_max))

49.07% is mean value obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
4.96 is standard deviation obtained using RepeatedStratifiedKFold CV.
There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 39.15 & 58.99

Observation:-¶

  • We are getting an average accuracy of almost 49.07%.
  • There is 95% chance that the accuracy of this model would be between 39.15% & 58.99% ie there is 5% chance that the accuracy of this model would greater than the maximum accuracy or lesser than the minimum accuracy.
In [226]:
KNNModelCntVtr.fit(X_trainCnt, y_trainCnt)
predKnnCntVtr = KNNModelCntVtr.predict(X_testCnt)

# check the accuracy on the training set
print('Accuracy on the train set (using Count Vectorizer) {}%'.format(KNNModelCntVtr.score(X_trainCnt, y_trainCnt) * 100))
# check the accuracy on the test set
accuracyKnnCntVtr = round(KNNModelCntVtr.score(X_testCnt, y_testCnt), 2) * 100
print('Accuracy on the test set (using Count Vectorizer) {}%'.format(accuracyKnnCntVtr))

KNNModelTfidfVtr.fit(X_trainTfidf, y_trainTfidf)
predKnnTfidfVtr = KNNModelTfidfVtr.predict(X_testTfidf)

# check the accuracy on the training set
print('Accuracy on the train set (using TF-IDF Vectorizer) {}%'.format(KNNModelTfidfVtr.score(X_trainTfidf, y_trainTfidf) * 100))
# check the accuracy on the test set
accuracyKnnTfidfVtr = round(KNNModelTfidfVtr.score(X_testTfidf, y_testTfidf), 2) * 100
print('Accuracy on the test set (using TF-IDF Vectorizer) {}%'.format(accuracyKnnTfidfVtr))

KNNModelTkn.fit(X_trainToken, y_trainToken)
predKnnTkn = KNNModelTkn.predict(X_testToken)

# check the accuracy on the training set
print('Accuracy on the train set (using Tokenizer) {}%'.format(KNNModelTkn.score(X_trainToken, y_trainToken) * 100))
# check the accuracy on the test set
accuracyKnnTkn = round(KNNModelTkn.score(X_testToken, y_testToken), 2) * 100
print('Accuracy on the test set (using Tokenizer) {}%'.format(accuracyKnnTkn))

Accuracy on the train set (using Count Vectorizer) 96.41434262948208%
Accuracy on the test set (using Count Vectorizer) 23.0%
Accuracy on the train set (using TF-IDF Vectorizer) 20.717131474103585%
Accuracy on the test set (using TF-IDF Vectorizer) 18.0%
Accuracy on the train set (using Tokenizer) 99.800796812749%
Accuracy on the test set (using Tokenizer) 51.0%

Observation:-¶

  • The model trained, using KNN, on training data is overfitted. This is the case when using count vectorizer & tokenizer.
  • The training accuracy, using KNN, is little higher than testing accuracy. This is the case when using TF-IDF vectorizer.

Classification report for KNN using CountVectorizer¶

mat = classification_report(y_testCnt, predKnnCntVtr, labels=['I','II','III','IV','V']);
print(mat)

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

           I       0.29      0.20      0.23        41
          II       0.27      0.27      0.27        48
         III       0.27      0.28      0.27        40
          IV       0.13      0.18      0.15        39
           V       0.23      0.22      0.22        46

    accuracy                           0.23       214
   macro avg       0.24      0.23      0.23       214
weighted avg       0.24      0.23      0.23       214

Observation:-¶

  • The recall for level I is 20%, level II is 27%, level III is 28%, level IV is 18% & level V is 22%.
  • The precision for level I is 29%, level II is 27%, level III is 27%, level IV is 13% & level V is 23%.
  • The f1-score for level I is 23%, level II is 27%, level III is 27%, level IV is 15% & level V is 22%.
  • The support for level I is 41, level II is 48, level III is 40, level IV is 39 & level V is 46.

Train and evaluate Deep Learning models¶

In [79]:
def convertCategoriesToIntforDf(df):
    df['PAL_toCategory'] = df['Potential Accident Level'].apply(lambda x: 0 if x == 'I' else (1 if x == 'II' else (2 if x == 'III' else (3 if x == 'IV' else 4))))
    return df
In [80]:
def convertCategoriesToInt(df):
    df_cat = []
    for x in df:
        if x == 'I':
            df_cat.append(0)
        if x == 'II':
            df_cat.append(1)
        if x == 'III':
            df_cat.append(2)
        if x == 'IV':
            df_cat.append(3)
        if x == 'V':
            df_cat.append(4)
    return df_cat
In [81]:
def convertIntToCategories(x):
    level = (lambda x: ('I' if x == 0 else ('II' if x == 1 else ('III' if x == 2 else ('IV' if x == 3 else 'V')))))(x)
    return level
In [97]:
def convertIntToCategoriesList(lst):
    catList = []
    for x in lst:
        catList.append((lambda x: ('I' if x == 0 else ('II' if x == 1 else ('III' if x == 2 else ('IV' if x == 3 else 'V')))))(x))
    return catList
In [82]:
def plotLossChart(history):
    plt.figure(figsize=(16,5))
    epochs = range(1, len(history.history['accuracy'])+1)
    plt.plot(epochs, history.history['loss'], 'b', label='Training Loss', color='red')
    plt.plot(epochs, history.history['val_loss'], 'b', label='Validation Loss')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
In [83]:
def plotAccuracyChart(history):
    plt.figure(figsize=(16,5))
    epochs = range(1, len(history.history['accuracy'])+1)
    plt.plot(epochs, history.history['accuracy'], 'b', label='Training Accuracy', color='red')
    plt.plot(epochs, history.history['val_accuracy'], 'b', label='Validation Accuracy')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
In [84]:
def getAccuracy(model, X_test, y_test):
    scores = model.evaluate(X_test, np.array(y_test), verbose=2)
    accuracy = scores[1]*100
    return accuracy
In [85]:
def convertPredictProbaToActualPrediction(y_pred):
    predList = []
    for prd in y_pred:
        predList.append(np.argmax(prd))
    return predList
In [86]:
y_trainToken_cat = convertCategoriesToInt(y_trainToken)
y_testToken_cat = convertCategoriesToInt(y_testToken)

Long-Short Term Memory (LSTM)¶

In [87]:
## Creating model

model_lstm = Sequential()
model_lstm.add(embeddingLayerTkn)
model_lstm.add(LSTM(30, dropout=0.1, return_sequences=True))
model_lstm.add(LSTM(15, dropout=0.1))
model_lstm.add(Dense(5, activation='softmax'))

# Compile model. Stochastic gradient descent with Nesterov accelerated gradient gives good results for this model
model_lstm.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])

print(model_lstm.summary())

  • Training accuracy also remained steady most of the time but has dropped at times. One can notice the sharp fall & rise spikes in training accuracy.
  • There is difference between validation accuracy & training accuracy.

Bi-directional Long-Short Term Memory (Bi-LSTM)¶

In [106]:
## Creating model

model_bilstm = Sequential()
model_bilstm.add(embeddingLayerTkn)
model_bilstm.add(Bidirectional(LSTM(64)))
model_bilstm.add(Dropout(0.3))
model_bilstm.add(Dense(5, activation='softmax'))

# Compile model. Stochastic gradient descent with Nesterov accelerated gradient gives good results for this model
sgd = SGD(lr=0.01, decay=1e-6, momentum=0.9, nesterov=True)
model_bilstm.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer=sgd, metrics=['accuracy'])

print(model_bilstm.summary())

Gated recurrent Units (GRU)¶

In [115]:
# The GRU architecture

model_gru = Sequential()
model_gru.add(embeddingLayerTkn)
model_gru.add(GRU(128, return_sequences=False))
model_gru.add(Dropout(0.5))
model_gru.add(Dense(5, activation = 'softmax'))

# Compile model. Stochastic gradient descent with Nesterov accelerated gradient gives good results for this model
model_gru.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='adam', metrics=['accuracy'])

print(model_gru.summary())

    • For Level V : we correctly classified level V : 168 (00+00+00+41+00+00+00+48+00+00+00+40+00+00+00+39)

  • False Positives (FP): Type I error

    • For Level I : we incorrectly classified level I : 41 (00+00+41+00)
    • For Level II : we incorrectly classified level II : 48 (00+00+48+00)
    • For Level III : we incorrectly classified level III : 40 (00+00+40+00)
    • For Level IV : we incorrectly classified level IV : 00 (00+00+00+00)
    • For Level V : we incorrectly classified level V : 46 (00+00+00+46)

  • False Negatives (FN): Type II error

    • For Level I : we incorrectly classified level I : 000 (00+00+00+00)
    • For Level II : we incorrectly classified level II : 000 (00+00+00+00)
    • For Level III : we incorrectly classified level III : 000 (00+00+00+00)

    • For Level V : we incorrectly classified level V : 000 (00+00+00+00)

In [131]:
def get_sentence_embeding(sentences):
    preprocessed_text = bert_preprocess(sentences)
    return bert_encoder(preprocessed_text)['pooled_output']

Getting embedding vectors for few sample words & comparing them using cosine similarity¶

In [132]:
e = get_sentence_embeding(["banana", "grapes", "mango", "jeff bezos", "elon musk", "bill gates"])
In [133]:
from sklearn.metrics.pairwise import cosine_similarity
cosine_similarity([e[0]],[e[1]])
Out[133]:
array([[0.99110883]], dtype=float32)

Observation:-¶

  • Values near to 1 means they are similar.
  • 0 means they are very different.
  • Comparing "banana" vs "grapes" we get 0.99 similarity as they both are fruits
In [134]:
cosine_similarity([e[0]],[e[3]])
Out[134]:
array([[0.84703857]], dtype=float32)

Observation:-¶

  • Comparing banana with jeff bezos still we get 0.84 but it is not as close as 0.99 ie they are not similar.
In [135]:
cosine_similarity([e[3]],[e[4]])
Out[135]:
array([[0.98720354]], dtype=float32)

Observation:-¶

  • Jeff bezos and Elon musk are more similar then Jeff bezos and banana.

Model building using Functional method¶

In [137]:
# Bert layers
text_input = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(), dtype=tf.string, name='text')
preprocessed_text = bert_preprocess(text_input)
outputs = bert_encoder(preprocessed_text)

# Neural network layers
l = tf.keras.layers.Dense(5, activation='softmax', name="output")(outputs['pooled_output'])
# Use inputs and outputs to construct a final model
model_bert = tf.keras.Model(inputs=[text_input], outputs = [l])

model_bert.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', optimizer='Adam', metrics=['accuracy'])
print(model_bert.summary())

Observation:-¶

  • The above Confusion Matrix has totals appended at the end. "total count actual class" - gives total count row-wise. "total count predicted" - gives total count column-wise.

  • True Positives (TP)

    • For Level I : we correctly classified level I : 26
    • For Level II : we correctly classified level II : 19
    • For Level III : we correctly classified level III : 14
    • For Level IV : we correctly classified level IV : 21
    • For Level V : we correctly classified level V : 32

  • True Negatives (TN):

    • For Level I : we correctly classified level I : 167 (19+09+11+01+09+14+11+04+06+17+21+08+01+00+04+32)
    • For Level II : we correctly classified level II : 151 (26+02+01+02+04+14+11+04+03+17+21+08+02+00+04+32)
    • For Level III : we correctly classified level III : 145 (26+03+01+02+05+19+11+01+03+06+21+08+02+01+04+32)
    • For Level IV : we correctly classified level IV : 133 (26+03+02+02+05+19+09+01+04+09+14+04+02+01+00+32)
    • For Level V : we correctly classified level V : 161 (26+03+02+01+05+19+09+11+04+09+14+11+03+06+17+21)

  • False Positives (FP): Type I error

    • For Level I : we incorrectly classified level I : 08 (03+02+01+02)
    • For Level II : we incorrectly classified level II : 26 (05+09+11+01)
    • For Level III : we incorrectly classified level III : 28 (04+09+11+04)
    • For Level IV : we incorrectly classified level IV : 34 (03+06+17+08)
    • For Level V : we incorrectly classified level V : 07 (02+01+00+04)

  • False Negatives (FN): Type II error

    • For Level I : we incorrectly classified level I : 14 (05+04+03+02)
    • For Level II : we incorrectly classified level II : 19 (03+09+06+01)
    • For Level III : we incorrectly classified level III : 28 (02+09+17+00)
    • For Level IV : we incorrectly classified level IV : 27 (01+11+11+04)
    • For Level V : we incorrectly classified level V : 15 (02+01+04+08)

           I       0.65      0.76      0.70        34

  • The f1-score for level I is 70%, level II is 46%, level III is 33%, level IV is 41% & level V is 74%.
  • The support for level I is 34, level II is 45, level III is 42, level IV is 55 & level V is 39.

Conclusion:-¶

  • From Accuracies perspective its clear that Bi-LSTM is a good model. Its accuracy is better than BERT & also its confusion matrix numbers alongwith Precision, F1, recall scores are better than BERT model.
  • There are primarily 2 reasons why we chose BERT model.
    1. Bi-LSTM model is overfitted.
    2. BERT is a pretrained model.
